It is more im· portant to note that Livy, our historian's other chief model, had prefixed to his narrative of Caesar’s war with Ariovistus an excursus described in terms very similar to the title which Tacitus is thought to have given to his own work ².

His other sources ofinformation are unknown to us but may well have been very numerous, Germans were often seen at Rome, and many Romans had been brought in contact with many tribes as officials in the provinces on the Rhine, or as traders in the interior. Even the distant north-east had lately been opened up by the amber traffie resulting from Roman luxury ³. The results of all this observation had probably occupied the minds of many antiquaries whose specu· ¹ lations are traceable in several places throughout the work ⁴.
